value.value: An increased chemical resistance phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells grow in the presence of a higher concentration of amiloride than normal.

label.value: increased resistance to chemical during vegetative growth

value.value: A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased resistance to a chemical stimulus. Resistance to a chemical is usually measured by determining the maximum concentration of the chemical at which a population of cells grow and divide, and cells are deemed resistant to a chemical if they survive at a concentration of the chemical that does not allow wild type cells to grow.

label.value: increased sensitivity to chemical during vegetative growth

value.value: A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show decreased resistance to a chemical stimulus. Resistance to a chemical is measured by determining the maximum concentration of the chemical at which a population of cells grow and divide. Typically, cells are deemed sensitive to a chemical if they stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of the chemical that allows wild type cells to grow.

A phenotype in which a cell requires a particular organic compound, which is not required by a wild-type cell for its growth. Auxotrophy usually results from a cell's inability to synthesize the compound.
A cell morphology phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell is formed in the shape of a sphere.
A spindle phenotype in which the spindle is shorter than normal.
A spindle phenotype in which mitotic spindle elongation, i.e. the process of lengthening the distance between poles of the mitotic spindle, is abnormal.
A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which primary cell septum disassembly is abnormal; may result in the formation of chains of attached cells.
A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell contains more than one nucleus, is longer than normal, and has a greater length:diameter ratio than normal.
A cell morphology phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell forms one or more branches near a septum, is elongated, and has more than one septum.
A localization phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the distribution of sterols in the plasma membrane is abnormal.
A phenotype that affects any physical object quality, such as morphology, number, location, etc., of a cell or a cellular component.

definition.value: This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

value.value: A cell phenotype that affects any mitotic cell cycle checkpoint.

definition.value: This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

value.value: A cell phenotype that affects the localization of a structure or substance in a cell.

definition.value: This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

value.value: A cell phenotype that affects the rate or extent of cell population growth. Cell population growth refers to an increase in the number of cells in the population as individual cells grow and divide.

definition.value: This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

value.value: A cellular process phenotype that affects metabolism in the cell.

definition.value: This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which mitotic sister chromatid segregation is abnormal. Mitotic sister chromatid segregation is the entire process in which replicated homologous chromosomes are organized and then physically separated and apportioned to two sets during the mitotic cell cycle.
A cellular process phenotype that affects gene expression. Gene expression includes transcription, RNA processing, and, for protein-coding genes, translation and protein maturation.

definition.value: This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

value.value: A gene expression phenotype that affects the regulation of DNA-dependent transcription.

definition.value: This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

value.value: A transcription regulation phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which chromatin silencing is abnormal. Chromatin silencing is the observed effect of processes that repress transcription in a region of the genome that is normally assembled into heterochromatin or CENP-A-containing chromatin (the latter is found at the centromere central core).

definition.value: Chromatin silencing phenotypes may reflect the assembly or maintenance of heterochromatin or CENP-A-containing chromatin. See the GO cellular component terms 'heterochromatin' (GO:0000792) and 'CENP-A containing chromatin' (GO:0061638), and the biological process terms 'heterochromatin organization' (GO:0070828) and 'CENP-A containing chromatin organization' (GO:0061641).

value.value: A cellular process phenotype that affects the regulation of a molecular function, biological process, or biological quality.

definition.value: This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

value.value: A transcription regulation phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which chromatin silencing is abnormal in centromeric regions. Chromatin silencing is the observed effect of processes that repress transcription in a region of the genome that is normally assembled into heterochromatin or CENP-A-containing chromatin (the latter is found at the centromere central core).

definition.value: Chromatin silencing phenotypes may reflect the assembly or maintenance of heterochromatin or CENP-A-containing chromatin. See the GO cellular component terms 'heterochromatin' (GO:0000792) and 'CENP-A containing chromatin' (GO:0061638), and the biological process terms 'heterochromatin organization' (GO:0070828) and 'CENP-A containing chromatin organization' (GO:0061641).

value.value: A regulation phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the switch from the monopolar to bipolar mode of cell growth (new end take-off; NETO) is abnormal.

label.value: abnormal regulation of mitotic cell cycle

value.value: A regulation phenotype in which regulation of the mitotic cell cycle is abnormal.
A cell process phenotype that affects a transport process.

definition.value: This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which the morphology, i.e. the size, shape, or structure, of a colony growing on a solid surface is abnormal.

A cellular process phenotype in which meiotic chromosome segregation is abnormal. Meiotic chromosome segregation is the entire process in which genetic material, in the form of chromosomes, is organized into specific structures and then physically separated and apportioned to two or more sets during M phase of the meiotic cell cycle.

label.value: abnormal cellular response to nitrogen starvation

value.value: A stress response phenotype in which the response to nitrogen starvation is abnormal.

definition.value: This term can be used for any circumstances in which cells are starved for nitrogen. Note that cells may enter G0 (quiescence) when subjected to prolonged nitrogen starvation; this term is not restricted to G0. Use this term if you have assayed the response to nitrogen starvation at the subcellular or molecular level. If you have assayed growth of cells exposed to nitrogen starvation in culture, use 'sensitive to nitrogen starvation' (FYPO:0002124).

label.value: abnormal negative regulation of G0 to G1 transition

value.value: A regulation phenotype in which negative regulation of the G0 to G1 transition is abnormal.
A cell population phenotype that reflects increased occurrence of flocculation. Flocculation is the non-sexual aggregation of single cells.

definition.value: Note that all normally occurring flocculation in S. pombe is galactose-specific, but other types of flocculation may abnormally occur.

label.value: abnormal chromatin silencing at silent mating-type cassette

value.value: A transcription regulation phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which chromatin silencing at the silent mating-type cassettes is abnormal. Chromatin silencing is the observed effect of processes that repress transcription in a region of the genome that is normally assembled into heterochromatin.

definition.value: Chromatin silencing phenotypes may reflect the assembly or maintenance of heterochromatin. See the GO cellular component term 'heterochromatin' (GO:0000792), and the biological process term 'heterochromatin organization' (GO:0070828).

label.value: abnormal response to DNA damage stimulus during vegetative growth

value.value: A stress response phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the response to DNA damage is abnormal.

definition.value: Use this term if you have assayed the response to DNA damage at the subcellular or molecular level. If you have assayed growth of cells exposed to DNA damage in culture, use 'sensitive to DNA damage' (FYPO:0000265). Also consider specific phenotype terms for sensitivity to substances or other stimuli that can damage DNA, e.g. 'sensitive to DNA damaging agents' (FYPO:0000266), 'sensitive to methyl methanesulfonate' (FYPO:0000089), 'sensitive to UV' (FYPO:0000268), etc.

label.value: DNA content increased during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the total amount of DNA in a cell is greater than normal.

A cellular process phenotype in which chromosome condensation is abnormal. Chromosome condensation is the progressive compaction of dispersed interphase chromatin into threadlike chromosomes prior to mitotic or meiotic nuclear division.
A cell phenotype in which DNA is broken into small fragments.

definition.value: Use 'fragmented DNA' (FYPO:0000160) or one of its descendants if DNA was detected using a method that can resolve molecule sizes (e.g. gel electrophoresis) or detect DNA ends (e.g. TUNEL assay). Otherwise, consider using 'fragmented nucleus' (FYPO:0001919) or one of its descendants.

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which contractile ring assembly is abnormal. Contractile ring assembly is the part of cytokinesis in which the actomyosin contractile ring is formed of actin, myosin, and associated proteins.
A cellular response phenotype in which a cellular response to stress is abnormal.

definition.value: Use a descendant of this term if you have assayed the response to a stress at the subcellular or molecular level. If you have assayed growth of cells exposed to the stress in culture, use a descendant of 'sensitive to stress' (FYPO:0002549) or 'resistance to stress' (FYPO:0002046).

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which macroautophagy is abnormal. Macroautophagy is the major pathway by which cells digest parts of their own cytoplasm.

A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cell separation after cytokinesis is abnormal. Cell separation is the process of physically separating progeny cells after cytokinesis is complete, and involves enzymatic digestion of septum components.
A regulation phenotype in which regulation of conjugation is abnormal.

label.value: abnormal regulation of G2/M transition of mitotic cell cycle

value.value: A regulation phenotype in which negative regulation of the G2 to M transition of the mitotic cell cycle is abnormal.

label.value: increased DNA recombination at mitotic DNA replication fork barriers

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the frequency of DNA recombination at replication fork barriers is increased.

A cell cycle checkpoint phenotype in which the spindle assembly checkpoint of a mitotic cell cycle is abnormal. The mitotic spindle assembly checkpoint normally delays the metaphase/anaphase transition of a mitotic nuclear division until the spindle is correctly assembled and chromosomes are attached to the spindle. In a mutant, the checkpoint may fail to arrest or delay cell cycle progression under appropriate conditions, or the incidence or duration of arrest or delay may differ from wild type under any specified set of conditions.

A transcription regulation phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which chromatin silencing at subtelomeric regions is abnormal. Chromatin silencing is the observed effect of processes that repress transcription in a region of the genome that is normally assembled into heterochromatin.

definition.value: Chromatin silencing phenotypes may reflect the assembly or maintenance of heterochromatin. See the GO cellular component term 'heterochromatin' (GO:0000792), and the biological process term 'heterochromatin organization' (GO:0070828).

label.value: abnormal late endosome to vacuole transport

value.value: A transport phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which late endosome to vacuole transport is abnormal.

definition.value: This term can be used for protein transport or for the movement of other substances (e.g. lipids or ions) from the late endosome to the vacuole. If it is used for a protein transport phenotype, we recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay.

value.value: A meiosis phenotype in which meiotic telomere clustering is abnormal. Meiotic telomere clustering is the dynamic reorganization of telomeres in early meiotic prophase, during which meiotic chromosome ends are gathered in a bouquet arrangement at the inner surface of the nuclear envelope proximal to the spindle pole body.

label.value: abnormal mitotic cell cycle DNA replication checkpoint

value.value: A cell cycle checkpoint phenotype in which the DNA replication checkpoint in a mitotic cell cycle is abnormal. The DNA replication checkpoint normally prevents the initiation of mitosis until DNA replication is complete. In a mutant, the checkpoint may fail to arrest or delay cell cycle progression under appropriate conditions, or the incidence or duration of arrest or delay may differ from wild type under any specified set of conditions.
A cellular process phenotype in which cell wall biogenesis is abnormal.
A sporulation phenotype in which ascospore wall assembly is abnormal.
A cellular process phenotype in which the initiation of DNA replication is abnormal.
